WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.300 --> 00:00:04.990
Prof: You're going to
get more numbers today.

00:00:04.990 --> 00:00:07.790
I know you--how many love
numbers?

00:00:07.790 --> 00:00:09.920
You can't live without numbers.
 

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:17.325
What did I tell you was the
traditional, before modern

00:00:17.325 --> 00:00:20.120
times, death rate?
 

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:22.828
A number you should keep,
or birth rate,

00:00:22.828 --> 00:00:25.120
it's the same--about per 1,000?
 

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:35.461
About 40 to 50 per 1,000 is the
birth and death rate at a life

00:00:35.461 --> 00:00:42.337
expectancy of 20 years,
that means 1/20th of the people

00:00:42.337 --> 00:00:47.271
die every year and so you need
50 out of 1,000 births 1/20th of

00:00:47.271 --> 00:00:50.912
your people to be births;
so births and deaths,

00:00:50.912 --> 00:00:53.200
in what we call primitive
times,

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:56.220
which might mean up to the
Napoleonic Revolution,

00:00:56.220 --> 00:01:04.780
almost is 40 to 50 births and
40 to 50 deaths a year.

00:01:04.780 --> 00:01:07.120
Now here is modern times.
 

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:11.305
We're starting in 1950 in all
of these graphs and coming in

00:01:11.305 --> 00:01:15.870
the period of the popular--
main--beginning births of the

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:20.470
population explosion 1950 to
1990 in all these cases.

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:25.165
And here are the various parts
of the world and you'll notice

00:01:25.165 --> 00:01:32.456
that this is the death--
I'm sorry the birth rate is 50,

00:01:32.456 --> 00:01:39.920
birth rate is 43 or something
42,43, 45,45.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:46.400
That 1950 the birth rate is at
approximately its level for

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:48.790
centuries way back.
 

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:53.174
We know that not too much
before this time since

00:01:53.174 --> 00:01:57.000
population was not growing until
some--

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.927
a little bit before this time
that the death rate must have

00:02:00.927 --> 00:02:04.872
been the same,
so the death rate was also 40

00:02:04.872 --> 00:02:06.219
to 50 people.
 

00:02:06.219 --> 00:02:07.299
Look what happened.
 

00:02:07.299 --> 00:02:12.536
By 1950 the death rate is
already down to half of its

00:02:12.536 --> 00:02:17.471
traditional level,
even in Sub-Saharan Africa it's

00:02:17.471 --> 00:02:21.322
almost reduced to half;
in Central America,

00:02:21.322 --> 00:02:23.169
the Caribbean,
less than half;

00:02:23.169 --> 00:02:26.759
South America less than half;
China about half;

00:02:26.759 --> 00:02:31.229
South Asia about half;
Southeast Asia about half.

00:02:31.229 --> 00:02:35.930
In most of the world by the
1950s the birthrate was still

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:39.455
extremely high,
but the death rate had come

00:02:39.455 --> 00:02:43.150
down to half of what it had
always been.

00:02:43.150 --> 00:02:47.627
What was going on is that these
countries were almost all still

00:02:47.627 --> 00:02:51.889
under colonial rule with the
exception of South America,

00:02:51.889 --> 00:02:55.250
which might be a reason why
it's even better.

00:02:55.250 --> 00:03:00.141
And, among all their faults,
the colonialists did institute

00:03:00.141 --> 00:03:03.276
basic sanitation,
basic public health,

00:03:03.276 --> 00:03:07.256
basic public order and they
stopped a lot of the warfare

00:03:07.256 --> 00:03:08.919
between communities.
 

00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:12.633
They imposed a lot of violence
upon the people but that was

00:03:12.633 --> 00:03:16.476
apparently much less then the
violence that local communities

00:03:16.476 --> 00:03:19.870
imposed upon each other in the
pre-colonial era,

00:03:19.870 --> 00:03:25.750
so the death rate was down by
the 1950s.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:28.156
Sometime in 50s,
around 1950,

00:03:28.156 --> 00:03:33.400
the birth rate started coming
down in all those countries,

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:36.756
and even though the birthrate
starts at these very,

00:03:36.756 --> 00:03:40.985
very high levels they come down
almost everywhere with of course

00:03:40.985 --> 00:03:43.940
the exception being Sub-Saharan
Africa,

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:46.807
and you've read about why that
is and I keep saying that almost

00:03:46.807 --> 00:03:50.354
everything we say,
SubSaharan Africa is an

00:03:50.354 --> 00:03:52.930
exception to the rate.
 

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:57.419
Even though the death rate was
down,

00:03:57.419 --> 00:04:00.206
the birth rate didn't change
much, but in every other part of

00:04:00.206 --> 00:04:02.020
the developing regions of the
world,

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:07.453
the birth rate and the death
rate came down approximately in

00:04:07.453 --> 00:04:09.938
parallel with each other.
 

00:04:09.938 --> 00:04:15.163
Of course the difference
between that birth and death

00:04:15.163 --> 00:04:20.988
rate is population increase -
and this is the heyday of the

00:04:20.988 --> 00:04:23.500
population explosion.
 

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:28.170
Remember this is per 1,000 so
it's a percent kind of a number,

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:31.954
so as the population grows the
number of people represented by

00:04:31.954 --> 00:04:34.190
this percent cap grows and
grows,

00:04:34.190 --> 00:04:40.148
and grows, and so this explains
the graph I showed you last

00:04:40.148 --> 00:04:46.519
time,
or two times ago.

00:04:46.519 --> 00:04:51.946
Starting again in 1950 to 1990,
the number of people added each

00:04:51.946 --> 00:04:55.899
year just keeps growing,
with one blip and you'll see

00:04:55.899 --> 00:04:59.550
later in the course,
I've shown you that blip

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:04.050
before, but we'll discuss what
that blip is.

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:07.843
The data for the individual
regions of the world and this

00:05:07.843 --> 00:05:10.079
all fits together,
makes sense.

00:05:10.079 --> 00:05:14.800
Now we've been through the
European population story,

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:17.040
and again we saw that,
not always but mostly,

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:20.649
the death rate fell first and
then the birth rate fell and

00:05:20.649 --> 00:05:23.500
Europe went through a population
explosion.

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:26.160
To say this story the way I've
been telling you,

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:29.096
no differences,
that the third world is just

00:05:29.096 --> 00:05:32.509
going through exactly what
Europe went through,

00:05:32.509 --> 00:05:34.610
but it isn't true.
 

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:40.560
Let's compare two of the
fertility transitions.

00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:46.137
This is Sweden and this is
Mexico, and you'll notice that

00:05:46.137 --> 00:05:52.113
Sweden has birth and death kind
of hanging around until maybe

00:05:52.113 --> 00:05:54.177
here,
until 1860s,

00:05:54.177 --> 00:05:59.161
and that's just what the
Princeton Project found out that

00:05:59.161 --> 00:06:04.233
the really serious decline
happened somewhere in this 1870

00:06:04.233 --> 00:06:08.697
region,
and then the death rate

00:06:08.697 --> 00:06:16.029
declines rather continuously on
through the time,

00:06:16.029 --> 00:06:17.860
and the birth rate declines.
 

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:20.360
This starts around 1870.
 

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:23.819
Mexico's decrease starts around
1970.

00:06:23.819 --> 00:06:27.495
So between what we now call the
developing countries or the

00:06:27.495 --> 00:06:30.940
third world countries,
about 100 year difference

00:06:30.940 --> 00:06:34.961
between when Europe started its
transition and when the

00:06:34.961 --> 00:06:38.610
developing countries started
their transition.

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:40.660
Now 100 years may seem a lot to
you,

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:42.680
but in the course of human
history,

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:47.060
since these numbers had been
going on forever,

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:50.129
100 years is a very,
very short time.

00:06:50.129 --> 00:07:08.452
Another difference you should
note is--Hang on,

00:07:08.452 --> 00:07:16.420
I just fixed this.
 

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:29.209
Usually that's all that
required I hope.

00:07:29.209 --> 00:07:40.459
Nope.
 

00:07:40.459 --> 00:07:52.279
Anybody have a laser pointer by
any miracle?

00:07:52.279 --> 00:07:56.254
All right, we're going to have
a little bit of trouble today

00:07:56.254 --> 00:07:58.949
but I think you can figure
things out.

00:07:58.949 --> 00:08:05.978
Notice that the levels of
everything there are lower in

00:08:05.978 --> 00:08:08.880
Sweden,
that Sweden starts and the

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:12.577
European countries generally
start at a lower level of births

00:08:12.577 --> 00:08:15.766
and a lower level of deaths,
so they were already,

00:08:15.766 --> 00:08:18.720
by the time that their serious
transition starts,

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:23.278
they're already quite a ways
down compared to where Mexico

00:08:23.278 --> 00:08:24.000
starts.
 

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:37.631
Notice that the deaths and the
births are much higher in Mexico

00:08:37.631 --> 00:08:41.370
than in Europe.
 

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:46.773
Now those are important,
but notice the gradualness of

00:08:46.773 --> 00:08:48.710
the decline here.
 

00:08:48.710 --> 00:08:53.029
That Sweden had a long time to
adjust to these changes,

00:08:53.029 --> 00:08:57.509
whereas, look at the drop in
the death rate in Mexico.

00:08:57.509 --> 00:08:58.990
Boom!
 

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:02.731
Basically all of a sudden and
then give it a generation,

00:09:02.731 --> 00:09:05.250
look at the drop in the birth
rate.

00:09:05.250 --> 00:09:10.488
That's the most amazing thing,
how rapidly things change in

00:09:10.488 --> 00:09:15.095
the developing world,
compared to the way it changed

00:09:15.095 --> 00:09:16.360
in Europe.
 

00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:22.778
Because of this rapidity of
this decline and a natural delay

00:09:22.778 --> 00:09:25.625
here,
whereas in Sweden that might be

00:09:25.625 --> 00:09:27.815
the delay,
the delay means because of the

00:09:27.815 --> 00:09:31.586
rapidity of the decline,
that the difference now between

00:09:31.586 --> 00:09:36.086
births and deaths is this huge
amount compared to a much

00:09:36.086 --> 00:09:37.970
smaller amount here.
 

00:09:37.970 --> 00:09:40.899
Europe never had to cope with
the rate of increase,

00:09:40.899 --> 00:09:43.360
the number of people added
every year,

00:09:43.360 --> 00:09:47.457
the percentage of the
population, never had to cope

00:09:47.457 --> 00:09:52.129
with anything like what the
currently developing countries

00:09:52.129 --> 00:09:55.899
had and that's a result of the
rapid drop.

00:09:55.899 --> 00:09:59.720
The other thing to note,
of course,

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:02.586
is that by this time,
the births and the deaths in

00:10:02.586 --> 00:10:06.407
Sweden are essentially equal,
and Sweden's population is not

00:10:06.407 --> 00:10:10.171
growing anymore and that as you
heard from Dr. Teitelbaum's

00:10:10.171 --> 00:10:13.486
lecture,
is characteristic of Europe as

00:10:13.486 --> 00:10:16.375
a whole,
as well as Japan,

00:10:16.375 --> 00:10:21.158
and a lot of the East Asian
countries.

00:10:21.158 --> 00:10:26.624
A cartoon of this which has--a
lot right about and one big

00:10:26.624 --> 00:10:30.179
thing wrong with it,
is that here's the rich

00:10:30.179 --> 00:10:33.817
countries, they start--
this is the pop--rate of

00:10:33.817 --> 00:10:38.946
increase of population growth,
that they start earlier,

00:10:38.946 --> 00:10:42.269
he starts it quite early in
France,

00:10:42.269 --> 00:10:46.582
and 100 years later--in this
graph it's called 'poor

00:10:46.582 --> 00:10:48.190
countries' start.
 

00:10:48.190 --> 00:10:51.918
The peak, the rise is slow,
the fall is slow,

00:10:51.918 --> 00:10:54.798
the rise is fast,
the fall is fast,

00:10:54.798 --> 00:10:57.509
the peak is much lower here.
 

00:10:57.509 --> 00:10:59.389
The peak is about 1%.
 

00:10:59.389 --> 00:11:04.567
The maximum rate of growth that
Europe ever experienced was 1%,

00:11:04.567 --> 00:11:09.326
whereas, for poor countries,
the average was 2.5% and some

00:11:09.326 --> 00:11:10.830
were up at 3%.
 

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:18.792
So, enormously greater stress
on the countries that went

00:11:18.792 --> 00:11:23.279
through this very,
very fast.

00:11:23.279 --> 00:11:26.360
Why did this happen?
 

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:28.288
Why is it so much faster in
developing countries?

00:11:28.288 --> 00:11:31.710
We say that as each country,
as it gets into their

00:11:31.710 --> 00:11:35.340
transition phase later,
everything happens faster.

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:38.210
It's quite a robust phenomenon.
 

00:11:38.210 --> 00:11:41.392
Every few years,
you say, oh man China or some

00:11:41.392 --> 00:11:43.317
country,
Korea, Taiwan,

00:11:43.317 --> 00:11:48.153
had the fastest decline ever
and then a few years later some

00:11:48.153 --> 00:11:52.990
new countries enter in and their
decline is even faster.

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:57.225
One of the main reasons is that
contraceptives were invented

00:11:57.225 --> 00:11:58.230
around here.
 

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:02.048
The pill, the diaphragm,
kind of all that--

00:12:02.048 --> 00:12:05.960
well some of them went way back
here but the modern method,

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:10.105
the really modern methods were
all like the pill in around the

00:12:10.105 --> 00:12:10.649
1960s.
 

00:12:10.649 --> 00:12:15.235
This is a graph showing that
the developing countries are

00:12:15.235 --> 00:12:18.644
using contraception,
so here is contraceptive

00:12:18.644 --> 00:12:20.777
prevalence,
the percent of women and

00:12:20.777 --> 00:12:23.120
childbearing ages that use
contraception,

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:28.450
and it ranges from very little,
less than 10% to like 70%.

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:29.160
The U.S.
 

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:31.649
is in the 60% to 70% range.
 

00:12:31.649 --> 00:12:34.408
Notice that the fertility,
the total fertility rate,

00:12:34.408 --> 00:12:36.740
if the country's not using
contraception,

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:40.433
very high fertility rate,
as they use more and more

00:12:40.433 --> 00:12:43.759
contraception their fertility
rate goes on.

00:12:43.759 --> 00:12:47.197
The mechanism in the developing
countries is use of

00:12:47.197 --> 00:12:50.500
contraception and mostly modern
contraception.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:53.227
Whereas, when Europe went
through its transition,

00:12:53.227 --> 00:12:55.730
they didn't have hardly any
contraception.

00:12:55.730 --> 00:13:00.695
Some condoms were just
beginning to come in but none of

00:13:00.695 --> 00:13:05.936
the modern chemical methods or
the better kinds of barrier

00:13:05.936 --> 00:13:07.038
methods.
 

00:13:07.038 --> 00:13:11.440
The story is kind of--that,
why the developing countries

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:15.519
are faster is that the science
is already there,

00:13:15.519 --> 00:13:19.331
the medical stuff is there,
the death rate comes down

00:13:19.331 --> 00:13:23.876
because again Europe developed
the medical know how and then it

00:13:23.876 --> 00:13:27.470
just got transferred very
rapidly: vaccines,

00:13:27.470 --> 00:13:31.543
vitamins, viruses,
all of those were discovered

00:13:31.543 --> 00:13:34.200
before the transition there.
 

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:38.413
Just as important as the
knowledge was an attitude toward

00:13:38.413 --> 00:13:42.024
civil government and civil
society that it is the

00:13:42.024 --> 00:13:46.841
responsibility of governments to
take care of the health of their

00:13:46.841 --> 00:13:47.820
people.
 

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:49.100
That's not a given.
 

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:51.119
Most countries,
through most of history,

00:13:51.119 --> 00:13:54.019
the government was rapacious
and their idea was to get as

00:13:54.019 --> 00:13:56.350
much taxes from the peasants as
possible.

00:13:56.350 --> 00:13:59.998
The peasants were sort of like
non-humans and use those taxes

00:13:59.998 --> 00:14:03.830
to have an army and go try to
get--enlarge their territories.

00:14:03.830 --> 00:14:07.850
The idea of civil government,
where the government is for the

00:14:07.850 --> 00:14:12.006
people is a fairly modern idea
and one of the basic things that

00:14:12.006 --> 00:14:14.889
governments try to do is public
health.

00:14:14.889 --> 00:14:19.320
Then of course--on the
technology,

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:22.447
the contraceptives I've
mentioned, the means of mass

00:14:22.447 --> 00:14:25.751
communication,
I'll show you a slide later

00:14:25.751 --> 00:14:30.528
that change in behavior is
triggered a lot by what you see

00:14:30.528 --> 00:14:34.549
on television and what you see
on the radio,

00:14:34.549 --> 00:14:37.240
what you see in newspapers.
 

00:14:37.240 --> 00:14:39.570
As in chimpanzees,
we're a very social species,

00:14:39.570 --> 00:14:42.053
and we're always looking to see
what's acceptable,

00:14:42.053 --> 00:14:44.080
what kind of behavior is
acceptable.

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:47.149
Gossip, maybe I mentioned this,
that most of what humans say to

00:14:47.149 --> 00:14:49.971
each other is gossip and the
function of gossip is to find

00:14:49.971 --> 00:14:52.350
what are the limits of
acceptable behavior,

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:56.976
so the mass media is extremely
important in like telling people

00:14:56.976 --> 00:15:01.678
in this case that two children
is the proper way of families.

00:15:01.678 --> 00:15:04.907
They see American television,
American movies,

00:15:04.907 --> 00:15:07.490
or Japanese,
and what do they see?

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:10.273
Rich people with two children,
whereas as they previously

00:15:10.273 --> 00:15:13.157
believed that in order to be
rich in some sense you have to

00:15:13.157 --> 00:15:18.500
have eight children,
so the media are very important

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:21.808
in changing perceptions.
 

00:15:21.808 --> 00:15:23.769
Also, for a very long time,
maybe not now,

00:15:23.769 --> 00:15:28.408
the West had--cachet--was
considered the future,

00:15:28.408 --> 00:15:31.375
the modernity,
the West was very respected and

00:15:31.375 --> 00:15:34.080
loved around the world and so
the use--

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:39.620
the small family norm was a
characteristic of the Western,

00:15:39.620 --> 00:15:42.840
a lot of people tried to become
like the West,

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:44.820
there was that cachet.
 

00:15:44.820 --> 00:15:47.307
Of course family planning
programs, the west had a long

00:15:47.307 --> 00:15:49.288
experience with family planning
programs.

00:15:49.288 --> 00:15:51.910
You've read some of the
Margaret Sanger stuff from

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:54.279
America,
the Marie Stopes stuff from

00:15:54.279 --> 00:15:56.647
England,
where people are struggling

00:15:56.647 --> 00:16:00.124
with these things and finally
come out the other end and

00:16:00.124 --> 00:16:02.970
decide to gain control of their
fertility.

00:16:02.970 --> 00:16:06.700
In a sense, both medically and
culturally,

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:11.663
Westerners were the guinea pigs
for this fertility transition

00:16:11.663 --> 00:16:14.629
and then once it was,
in some sense,

00:16:14.629 --> 00:16:17.220
perfected and finished in the
West,

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:22.918
it was sort of transferred
wholesale to the newly

00:16:22.918 --> 00:16:25.649
developing countries.
 

00:16:25.649 --> 00:16:31.052
Now another thing about the
fertility transition is that not

00:16:31.052 --> 00:16:35.724
only is it more intense
demographically with all the

00:16:35.724 --> 00:16:40.956
statistics that we can gather,
but it's also more intense

00:16:40.956 --> 00:16:41.970
emotionally.
 

00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:46.759
As you're for sure well aware
by now in this course,

00:16:46.759 --> 00:16:50.732
there's enormously strong
social norms about sex and

00:16:50.732 --> 00:16:53.972
reproduction,
and if those norms are about to

00:16:53.972 --> 00:16:57.765
change it attacks one of the
most important foundations of a

00:16:57.765 --> 00:17:02.214
culture and there's--
that does not happen without a

00:17:02.214 --> 00:17:05.700
lot of conflict within the
culture.

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:09.268
In the West,
although there's a lot of

00:17:09.268 --> 00:17:13.368
discussion about this,
the idea of individualism,

00:17:13.368 --> 00:17:17.400
that people individually go out
and do what's good for them,

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:20.298
they make choices based on
their own desires.

00:17:20.298 --> 00:17:23.454
There's kind of a long history
of that and it was sort of

00:17:23.454 --> 00:17:26.160
formalized by Adam Smith in
economics saying,

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:29.444
that if everybody went out and
tried to get as rich as possible

00:17:29.444 --> 00:17:31.460
it would be wonderful for
everybody.

00:17:31.460 --> 00:17:34.308
In most of the developing
countries they have a more

00:17:34.308 --> 00:17:38.384
communal kind of attitude,
whereas, often if you speak to

00:17:38.384 --> 00:17:39.913
older,
say Chinese,

00:17:39.913 --> 00:17:44.358
or Indians--the smallest unit
of desire which they speak of is

00:17:44.358 --> 00:17:46.941
the family;
very hard to get them to think

00:17:46.941 --> 00:17:47.930
of what THEY want.
 

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:51.676
It's the family,
or village, or some larger

00:17:51.676 --> 00:17:52.480
entity.
 

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:57.018
When you start changing norms,
the norms in non-Western

00:17:57.018 --> 00:18:02.311
societies or pre-modern western
societies are very much stronger

00:18:02.311 --> 00:18:04.750
in control of the people.
 

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:07.788
People have less latitude to go
and do their own thing;

00:18:07.788 --> 00:18:13.848
they're under social--much more
social control.

00:18:13.848 --> 00:18:18.512
Of course all of these things
multiply--square these things,

00:18:18.512 --> 00:18:22.150
quadruple them,
if you're talking about sex.

00:18:22.150 --> 00:18:24.215
One of the readings,
I don't know if you're going to

00:18:24.215 --> 00:18:26.526
do it tonight or you did it
already, about the Palestinian

