00:20:47.614 --> 00:20:52.109
father-in-law and her own father
insists on killing her.

00:20:52.109 --> 00:20:54.288
That's from India.
 

00:20:54.288 --> 00:20:58.368
You have to contrast this with,
not all cultures are like this,

00:20:58.368 --> 00:21:05.390
so contrast this very tight
strict norm about women's--

00:21:05.390 --> 00:21:08.267
not giving women any
possibility for going beyond the

00:21:08.267 --> 00:21:10.315
norm,
compare it with the Na of China

00:21:10.315 --> 00:21:12.180
which I think you've already
read,

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:14.868
where everything is totally
free, or the Japanese,

00:21:14.868 --> 00:21:18.380
the story of the Suye Mura
women;

00:21:18.380 --> 00:21:20.269
have you read that yet?
 

00:21:20.269 --> 00:21:22.960
Again, there's a huge amount of
sexual freedom.

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:29.098
So it isn't that all cultures
have the same cultural norms,

00:21:29.098 --> 00:21:34.548
but they all do have cultural
norms and violation of those

00:21:34.548 --> 00:21:37.798
cultural norms will be punished.
 

00:21:37.798 --> 00:21:41.078
Another thing is that,
in the different stream,

00:21:41.078 --> 00:21:44.759
the Western and Eastern
fertility transition,

00:21:44.759 --> 00:21:48.532
is that the economic
constraints, the level of

00:21:48.532 --> 00:21:53.647
poverty in the third world is
much worse than it was in Europe

00:21:53.647 --> 00:21:56.500
at the time of its transition.
 

00:21:56.500 --> 00:22:00.347
Everything is more difficult
when you're poor and you live in

00:22:00.347 --> 00:22:03.363
a poor country with poorly
developed government,

00:22:03.363 --> 00:22:05.480
everything is more difficult.
 

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:10.999
In your reading packet is a one
page collection of headlines

00:22:10.999 --> 00:22:16.611
from Tanzania and you just see
all the problems that Tanzania

00:22:16.611 --> 00:22:22.223
is going through in a period
when their fertility is high and

00:22:22.223 --> 00:22:26.338
maybe beginning to start falling
down.

00:22:26.338 --> 00:22:32.977
We have some understanding of
the many ways in which

00:22:32.977 --> 00:22:36.479
statistically,
except by magnitude,

00:22:36.479 --> 00:22:39.638
the fertility of the
demographic transition in the

00:22:39.638 --> 00:22:43.380
countries that have entered
since 1960 looks very different

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:45.960
from those that entered it in
1860.

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:50.010
Quantitatively also,
when you go through a period of

00:22:50.010 --> 00:22:53.121
population growth,
the question is well how much

00:22:53.121 --> 00:22:55.904
did your population grow
altogether between the beginning

00:22:55.904 --> 00:22:58.886
of the transition which we've
had the beginning in Europe and

00:22:58.886 --> 00:23:04.395
the end in Europe,
as your text says something

00:23:04.395 --> 00:23:14.309
like 1870 to 1930 and Europe
grew by about a factor of four,

00:23:14.309 --> 00:23:16.970
so the population quadrupled.
 

00:23:16.970 --> 00:23:19.787
This was the time when the
population of the developing

00:23:19.787 --> 00:23:21.509
countries was staying constant.
 

00:23:21.509 --> 00:23:24.548
But developing countries--India
actually,

00:23:24.548 --> 00:23:27.474
as far as we can predict,
is having one of the smallest

00:23:27.474 --> 00:23:30.949
between four and five,
so they're sort of at the

00:23:30.949 --> 00:23:34.269
maximum for Europe,
no country in Europe was more

00:23:34.269 --> 00:23:36.921
than four and India,
one of the lowest countries for

00:23:36.921 --> 00:23:39.730
the developing world,
would be somewhere between four

00:23:39.730 --> 00:23:41.000
and five so we expect.
 

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:45.308
Mexico will have grown by a
factor of seven to ten times;

00:23:45.308 --> 00:23:49.680
Kenya by more than fifteen
times, so here is again,

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:52.150
countries that started the
transition poor,

00:23:52.150 --> 00:23:56.755
they're still moderately poor,
Mexico is doing better but

00:23:56.755 --> 00:24:01.690
certainly Kenya is not and India
is doing somewhat better.

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:05.537
And now they have to cope with
five, six, seven,

00:24:05.537 --> 00:24:09.140
eight, nine,
ten times as much population.

00:24:09.140 --> 00:24:13.045
Because of these multipliers,
the fraction of people in the

00:24:13.045 --> 00:24:17.017
different parts of the world
goes first one way and then the

00:24:17.017 --> 00:24:17.960
other way.
 

00:24:17.960 --> 00:24:22.208
Before the mortality
transition, Europeans

00:24:22.208 --> 00:24:27.390
represented about 18% of the
world's population.

00:24:27.390 --> 00:24:30.078
At its maximum,
when Europe had the maximum,

00:24:30.078 --> 00:24:32.180
Europe and European people in
America,

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:33.868
Australia, New Zealand and so
forth,

00:24:33.868 --> 00:24:37.660
but European stock people their
fraction--

00:24:37.660 --> 00:24:40.230
the European fraction of the
world population doubled,

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:45.089
more than doubled actually
from--about doubled from 18% to

00:24:45.089 --> 00:24:47.127
35% so they--
Europe was

00:24:47.127 --> 00:24:51.226
undergoing--Europeans were
undergoing a huge population

00:24:51.226 --> 00:24:51.910
thing.
 

00:24:51.910 --> 00:24:57.509
Now--by 1995 because Europe's
population growth is over,

00:24:57.509 --> 00:25:01.940
European people's are over,
and the developing countries

00:25:01.940 --> 00:25:06.612
population growth is starting
it's back to where it started

00:25:06.612 --> 00:25:09.108
and it's back to about 18%.
 

00:25:09.108 --> 00:25:13.765
Now--that's 1995 and we've had
already 13 years of population

00:25:13.765 --> 00:25:17.877
growth continuing in the
developing countries and it's

00:25:17.877 --> 00:25:21.058
continuing and getting more and
more.

00:25:21.058 --> 00:25:25.818
The relative percentage of
people in,

00:25:25.818 --> 00:25:29.433
what's now called the
developing world versus the

00:25:29.433 --> 00:25:32.701
European world,
is going now to be so high in

00:25:32.701 --> 00:25:36.522
the developing countries that
it's way beyond anything that

00:25:36.522 --> 00:25:41.040
was historically the case,
except maybe when humans

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:47.500
started moving out of Africa and
into the Middle East and into

00:25:47.500 --> 00:25:48.558
Europe.
 

00:25:48.558 --> 00:25:52.711
This may not stabilize--so far
there is no sign that European

00:25:52.711 --> 00:25:55.374
population,
almost all of the European

00:25:55.374 --> 00:25:59.347
populations now have fertility
rates below 2.1 and so they are

00:25:59.347 --> 00:26:01.626
going--
if they continue with that of

00:26:01.626 --> 00:26:04.210
course they eventually disappear
altogether,

00:26:04.210 --> 00:26:09.224
and the idea that there's going
to be some stabilization at some

00:26:09.224 --> 00:26:13.285
ratio of say rich and poor
countries is dependent on

00:26:13.285 --> 00:26:18.299
fertility coming up in developed
countries and we don't have any

00:26:18.299 --> 00:26:20.528
reason to expect that.
 

00:26:20.528 --> 00:26:23.278
This is an important factor
because,

00:26:23.278 --> 00:26:30.028
if part of the developing
countries coming out of poverty,

00:26:30.028 --> 00:26:33.318
is aid from the West and that's
again--

00:26:33.318 --> 00:26:35.769
everything is debatable in this
course,

00:26:35.769 --> 00:26:38.410
how much help aid does.
 

00:26:38.410 --> 00:26:39.999
It actually--there's no
question about that in some

00:26:39.999 --> 00:26:41.078
cases it's tremendously helpful.
 

00:26:41.078 --> 00:26:46.112
That if there's nobody left in
the developed countries to give

00:26:46.112 --> 00:26:50.641
the aid,
then one of the props which

00:26:50.641 --> 00:26:58.420
helps developing countries come
up will have disappeared.

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:02.769
We've gone through the
quantities of the transition,

00:27:02.769 --> 00:27:06.042
but we have compared the
demographic transition of

00:27:06.042 --> 00:27:09.250
developing countries with
European countries,

00:27:09.250 --> 00:27:15.410
but we haven't compared it to
anything else.

00:27:15.410 --> 00:27:21.271
The world population,
as I say, is growing something

00:27:21.271 --> 00:27:25.640
like 70 to 80 million people a
year.

00:27:25.640 --> 00:27:29.012
The question is,
if we imagine some sort of a

00:27:29.012 --> 00:27:32.615
landing for this,
what kinds of things are going

00:27:32.615 --> 00:27:35.529
to stop this population
explosion?

00:27:35.529 --> 00:27:38.279
There's bad things and there's
good things;

00:27:38.279 --> 00:27:41.210
bad possibilities and good
possibilities.

00:27:41.210 --> 00:27:45.338
The bad possibilities and have
been known--

00:27:45.338 --> 00:27:48.279
have been thought about for a
long time is 1) famine,

00:27:48.279 --> 00:27:51.529
that people could start
starving, disease,

00:27:51.529 --> 00:27:54.291
AIDS, people are always talking
about Aids balancing the

00:27:54.291 --> 00:27:55.798
population explosion or war.
 

00:27:55.798 --> 00:27:59.752
I'm going to give you some idea
of the magnitude of these

00:27:59.752 --> 00:28:00.460
factors.
 

00:28:00.460 --> 00:28:04.000
Famine, one way that famine
operates is,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.400
some country has a big drought
and they go through a short

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:11.220
period of terrible famine,
but that's not the main thing.

00:28:11.220 --> 00:28:15.990
People all over world and
especially children are

00:28:15.990 --> 00:28:20.858
malnourished and malnourished
leads to disease.

00:28:20.858 --> 00:28:25.063
It's very hard to get these
statistics and to gather these

00:28:25.063 --> 00:28:29.118
statistics, and it depends on
who you're talking too.

00:28:29.118 --> 00:28:33.017
I was teaching in a health
course and we sort of did serial

00:28:33.017 --> 00:28:37.082
lectures and Michelle Barry,
a professor of international

00:28:37.082 --> 00:28:41.298
infectious diseases,
gave the lecture before mine,

00:28:41.298 --> 00:28:46.250
so I went to her lecture to see
the lay of the land,

00:28:46.250 --> 00:28:50.190
and she was describing millions
of deaths from various diseases.

00:28:50.190 --> 00:28:52.358
The medical students,
this was to medical students,

00:28:52.358 --> 00:28:55.622
had no clue and they were just
absolutely shocked at the

00:28:55.622 --> 00:28:58.924
magnitude of what's going on,
especially in developing

00:28:58.924 --> 00:28:59.568
countries.
 

00:28:59.568 --> 00:29:01.642
She was listing,
maybe you know,

00:29:01.642 --> 00:29:04.983
Aids is about--back then it was
two million a year,

00:29:04.983 --> 00:29:08.058
it might be three million and
coming down;

00:29:08.058 --> 00:29:11.931
Malaria, tuberculosis from the
one to two million deaths a year

00:29:11.931 --> 00:29:14.558
kind of thing;
diarrhea in children, etc.

00:29:14.558 --> 00:29:19.170
These are--the massive killers
in the world.

00:29:19.170 --> 00:29:22.450
Next week I came on and said,
you know what,

00:29:22.450 --> 00:29:26.271
there's x millions of deaths
from malnutrition and they were

00:29:26.271 --> 00:29:29.704
shocked because it was an even
bigger number then what

00:29:29.704 --> 00:29:31.390
Dr. Barry had given.
 

00:29:31.390 --> 00:29:34.637
I said, you know what,
they're the same deaths you

00:29:34.637 --> 00:29:36.230
heard about last week.
 

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:39.920
The thing is something like--I
don't remember the number,

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:43.358
something like if you take a
skin test for tuberculosis,

00:29:43.358 --> 00:29:47.622
something like a third to a
half of us have been exposed to

00:29:47.622 --> 00:29:51.368
the TB bug so that we have
antibodies against it.

00:29:51.368 --> 00:29:54.244
We basically in some sense,
in a small sense,

00:29:54.244 --> 00:29:55.160
have had TB.
 

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:59.239
If you go to India more people
have had it but the fraction

00:29:59.239 --> 00:30:02.334
that actually come down and get
sick is much,

00:30:02.334 --> 00:30:03.460
much higher.
 

00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:04.119
Why?
 

00:30:04.119 --> 00:30:05.318
Malnutrition.
 

00:30:05.318 --> 00:30:08.017
That all of the diseases,
if you're malnourished your

00:30:08.017 --> 00:30:10.923
immune system and your other
body systems can't fight the

00:30:10.923 --> 00:30:13.635
bug,
so you actually get sick and

00:30:13.635 --> 00:30:14.920
will often die.
 

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:21.291
There's a big discussion of
when you see a death to say TB,

00:30:21.291 --> 00:30:27.773
is that death caused by the
tuberculosis bacillus or is that

00:30:27.773 --> 00:30:31.400
death caused by malnutrition?
 

00:30:31.400 --> 00:30:35.873
The World Health Organization
and a lot of other groups are

00:30:35.873 --> 00:30:40.654
now saying that the about half
the deaths from all these things

00:30:40.654 --> 00:30:44.279
are really at base caused by
malnutrition,

00:30:44.279 --> 00:30:47.470
that at the level of infection
that the people are exposed to,

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:52.538
you should see so many deaths
but you actually see twice that

00:30:52.538 --> 00:30:55.920
many deaths because people are
hungry.

00:30:55.920 --> 00:30:59.710
The numbers from the Food and
Agriculture Organization of the

00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:04.660
